So, I was walking by the place the other night and a friend told me that he had gone here a few times. He said it was a family-run place by some Russians who had been cutting hair for five generations. He also said that the father's old Soviet uniform was on display and that they gave you free beer while you waited. We had been drinking a bit before that I thought he was just making this all up. Thank God he wasn't.  The next day I stopped in for a hair cut and it was honestly one of the best that I've had. It was just like how my friend described it, Soviet uniform, free beer and all. Boris, one of the owner's sons,  was the only one there but he was really cool and friendly. He's a fifth generation barber with a 120 year family history of cutting hair and you can really tell that he knows what he's doing; and he does it very well too. I'd never been to a real barbershop before but this place was the real deal. The Downtown Barber Shop really lived up to my expections and then some. You can tell that the family who runs this place is passionate about what they do and that they really appreciate your service and in my book that makes this place a step above most others.   Generally, I don't give out five stars that much, but this barbershop really deserves it.  I'd give it six for the Monica Bellucci picture on the wall alone.

